WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.700
Your clock's running.

00:00:00.900 --> 00:00:01.900
Yeah, I saw it.

00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:02.300
All right.

00:00:03.160 --> 00:00:07.500
So we all know the current treatment approach for FLT3-mutated AML includes a FLT3 inhibitor.

00:00:07.600 --> 00:00:09.940
The approved drugs here are in red.

00:00:09.940 --> 00:00:13.920
And the reason that we have these drugs and they are approved is because, hey, they work.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:14.900
They improve survival.

00:00:15.120 --> 00:00:19.860
And you only need 14 days of FLT3 inhibitor during induction or consolidation, plus or

00:00:19.860 --> 00:00:24.180
minus maintenance, which was done on these studies, to show a survival advantage with

00:00:24.180 --> 00:00:24.860
this approach.

00:00:25.920 --> 00:00:29.880
The problem with this is if we look at the patients who aren't getting intensive chemotherapy,

00:00:30.160 --> 00:00:35.180
a current standard of care is not actually to give a targeted inhibitor front line because

00:00:35.180 --> 00:00:38.060
it hasn't been shown in a randomized setting to improve survival.

00:00:38.060 --> 00:00:41.960
I'm going to talk about some of the data that I think are leading towards studies that

00:00:41.960 --> 00:00:44.220
hopefully will confirm a benefit for that approach.

00:00:45.640 --> 00:00:52.160
If we look at what Veneza does for FLT3-positive patients, we know overall for VLEA, there

00:00:52.160 --> 00:00:55.600
was a survival benefit for patients treated with a combination over-aided placebo.

00:00:56.140 --> 00:00:59.540
But when we look at the FLT3-mutated patients, while it does look like their survival is

00:00:59.540 --> 00:00:59.780
better.

00:00:59.880 --> 00:01:05.880
That's almost entirely attributed to the FLT3-TKD-positive patients, as was shown on

00:01:05.880 --> 00:01:08.680
follow-up data that Marina Karnopleva had published.

00:01:09.200 --> 00:01:14.120
The FLT3-positive patients have overlapping survival with the non-FLT3-mutated patients.

00:01:14.120 --> 00:01:16.100
So no clear benefit of adding VEN.

00:01:16.100 --> 00:01:22.040
And indeed, the ELN 2024 classification for lower-intensity therapy shows FLT3 to

00:01:22.040 --> 00:01:23.420
be a lower-benefit group.

00:01:23.500 --> 00:01:24.880
So what can we do to improve outcome?

00:01:25.440 --> 00:01:29.760
We can improve remission rates with adding venetoclax to azacitidine, but it doesn't

00:01:29.760 --> 00:01:30.740
actually improve survival.

00:01:31.200 --> 00:01:33.540
Well, we have drugs that are effective in the salvage setting.

00:01:33.620 --> 00:01:34.720
What if we move them forward?

00:01:35.260 --> 00:01:39.740
We've looked at gilturitinib frontline with low-intensity therapy, initially with azacitidine

00:01:39.740 --> 00:01:40.100
alone.

00:01:40.120 --> 00:01:43.860
That actually was halted early because it was clear there was no survival benefit.

00:01:44.400 --> 00:01:48.040
Maybe a little better outcome in patients with high allyl burden, but the differences

00:01:48.040 --> 00:01:48.600
are small.

00:01:50.040 --> 00:01:53.960
There's been VEN plus gilt data in the relapsed refractory setting.

00:01:54.140 --> 00:01:59.180
And in the interest of time, I've not included those data other than to say it's feasible.

00:01:59.640 --> 00:02:00.460
It's tolerable.

00:02:00.720 --> 00:02:01.960
It's very mildly suppressive.

00:02:02.600 --> 00:02:07.240
So with that setting the stage, venetoclax azacitidine and gilturitinib was developed as a

00:02:07.240 --> 00:02:12.660
triplet, initially at MD Anderson, single-institution study, initially in the relapsed refractory

00:02:12.660 --> 00:02:17.720
setting, showing very similarly high remission rates to ven gilt in that population, but

00:02:17.720 --> 00:02:22.440
really remarkable response rates in the frontline setting in newly diagnosed patients, where

00:02:22.440 --> 00:02:28.740
the complete remission rates here were 90%, another 6% for CRI, and these remission rates

00:02:28.740 --> 00:02:29.520
actually exceed what we've seen.

00:02:29.520 --> 00:02:32.280
What we see for intensive chemotherapy at any age.

00:02:32.580 --> 00:02:33.960
So this is really impressive data.

00:02:33.960 --> 00:02:37.500
And while it's a small number of patients that have been treated, only about 20 of these are

00:02:37.500 --> 00:02:40.380
FLT3 FLT3 positive, and there are FLT3 TKDs here.

00:02:41.040 --> 00:02:44.520
I think everybody kind of was taken aback by just how good the data looked for this.

00:02:44.520 --> 00:02:46.980
And the question would be, you know, how long would this hold up?

00:02:46.980 --> 00:02:48.240
Would it improve survival?

00:02:48.280 --> 00:02:49.460
Are you getting deep remissions?

00:02:49.460 --> 00:02:53.980
And the answer to all of these is it looks a lot better than we're seeing with other regimens.

00:02:54.240 --> 00:02:57.720
The survivals do look better in non-randomized data.

00:02:57.720 --> 00:02:59.160
These are all single arm studies.

00:02:59.400 --> 00:03:05.160
They do achieve deep remissions in terms of FLT3 FLT3 burden reduction by ultra-sensitive FLT3 FLT3,

00:03:05.160 --> 00:03:12.540
NGS, MRD, the majority of patients actually clear detectable FLT3 FLT3 by in vivo scribe.

00:03:13.380 --> 00:03:16.140
And the downside to it is just the degree of myelosuppression, again,

00:03:16.140 --> 00:03:20.040
that when you add Ven and Gil together, it takes a very long time to recover your counts.

00:03:20.040 --> 00:03:23.700
Now, they were not seeing early mortality, but we always wonder, is that the Houston water?

00:03:23.700 --> 00:03:27.000
There's something about treating patients in Houston, and they just do better.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:29.280
So what we really want to know is, can we do this everywhere?

00:03:29.280 --> 00:03:30.420
Not just here.

00:03:30.420 --> 00:03:34.060
And so, oh, and I should also say this was not due to transplant.

00:03:34.060 --> 00:03:39.580
When they looked at the patients that went on to transplant, there was not an obvious survival benefit for the transplanted patients.

00:03:39.580 --> 00:03:41.260
It really just looks like the regimen.

00:03:41.260 --> 00:03:43.800
And some of this has to do with treating older patients.

00:03:43.800 --> 00:03:49.920
The median age on this study, I think, is 74 years and a high non-relapse mortality, obviously, in this older group.

00:03:51.240 --> 00:03:53.340
So can we do this everywhere is the question.

00:03:53.340 --> 00:03:59.160
And this was the reason for putting the Viceroy study together, which was a pharma-sponsored study that was multi-adjusted.

00:03:59.160 --> 00:04:05.660
And it was a study that was a little bit more traditional, but also both community oncology groups and also academic centers.

00:04:05.660 --> 00:04:11.040
So it was really trying to get a sense of can you do this anywhere.

00:04:11.040 --> 00:04:21.240
And while we looked at two different doses of venetoclax, 200 milligrams and 400 milligrams, in the end, actually, there wasn't a big difference in terms of response rates to either of the doses.

00:04:21.240 --> 00:04:23.380
They were both similarly high.

00:04:23.380 --> 00:04:29.040
Again, nearly everybody went into a protocol-defined CR, CRI, or CRH.

00:04:29.040 --> 00:04:32.960
And the survivals here look pretty much overlapping with what was experienced from MDN.

00:04:32.960 --> 00:04:35.220
So it's not actually the water in Houston.

00:04:35.220 --> 00:04:37.740
And this can be done outside of the bubble.

00:04:37.740 --> 00:04:43.020
And we did look at MRD clearance and similarly high, although the numbers here are very, very small.

00:04:43.020 --> 00:04:49.100
So it kind of sets the stage for what we're doing with myelomatch, which is we have very exciting single-arm data.

00:04:49.100 --> 00:04:50.760
What can we do in a randomized setting?

00:04:50.760 --> 00:04:56.600
Can we actually move the needle by showing, you know, once and for all, that really adds value to add a third drug here?

00:04:56.600 --> 00:04:58.920
And so the myelomatch study, as I've described before, it's very, very important.

00:04:58.920 --> 00:05:23.760
And it's nice to be described by Dr. Weiner here, randomizes patients who are not considered ideal candidates for intensive chemotherapy, either by age or comorbidity, generally people over the age of 60, to either vaneza as a standard arm, given just as it was done on the VLEA study, or one of two triplet regimens, one where the regimen is pretty much exactly as given on Nick Short's study from Anderson.

00:05:23.760 --> 00:05:28.520
And the other is where we tried to do it kind of as it's done in the setting of intensive chemotherapy.

00:05:28.800 --> 00:05:34.980
Where you give 14 days of giltaritinib after vaneza, which is given for seven days.

00:05:35.020 --> 00:05:39.960
And we wanted to actually start the gilt then, but AbbVie got very upset and said, we need the synergy of giving it together.

00:05:40.040 --> 00:05:40.740
So we said, fine.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:47.000
So there is actually seven days of overlap of the venetoclax and the azacitidine on each of the cycles.

00:05:48.580 --> 00:05:50.380
We shall see how this all turns out.

00:05:50.440 --> 00:05:58.680
But I think ultimately the question is, if it turns out as good as what we have seen, we now have two really good options from frontline for somebody eligible for any.

00:05:58.680 --> 00:06:07.640
You could get intensive chemotherapy plus a TKI and go on to intensive chemotherapy and a TKI if you're not going to go on to transplant or go on to a transplant.

00:06:07.920 --> 00:06:15.260
You could get venetoclax, azacitidine, and giltaritinib and get whatever is appropriate based on, again, MRD clearance, perhaps.

00:06:15.860 --> 00:06:28.560
Or maybe we need to be doing a study that's doing this, which is to randomize and say, really, if we have two good options and one is probably a heck of a lot easier, similar to what we've shown in Paradigm, do we really need intensive chemotherapy to achieve long-term fantastic therapy?

00:06:28.560 --> 00:06:32.340
We're seeing fantastic outcomes compared to what we used to see for FLT3 mutated patients.

00:06:32.700 --> 00:06:34.120
These look really much better.

00:06:34.840 --> 00:06:39.860
And I really must say we're seeing fewer and fewer relapses of FLT3 mutated patients no matter what we're doing frontline.

00:06:40.020 --> 00:06:47.540
And it's really heartening to see 80-year-old patients who are two and three years out from initial diagnosis still in remission with these kinds of approaches.

00:06:47.540 --> 00:06:49.060
And we are seeing that regularly.

00:06:49.660 --> 00:06:50.980
We never saw this before.

00:06:51.120 --> 00:06:52.420
So it's really exciting to see this.

00:06:52.660 --> 00:06:58.380
And just in conclusion, we are going to clearly improve remission rates with this approach.

00:06:58.440 --> 00:07:00.940
The big question is, is there value to it?

00:07:01.500 --> 00:07:04.420
Myelomatch is not designed to give definitive treatment effects.

00:07:04.780 --> 00:07:06.120
It's a signal-finding design.

00:07:06.120 --> 00:07:10.360
But I hope that we will at least provide a strong signal that says that there's something real about this.

00:07:10.840 --> 00:07:15.200
I do think vanadizagil could be an attractive approach for younger, fitter patients.

00:07:15.580 --> 00:07:20.080
And randomized studies of those kinds of approaches are actually in the works for this year.

00:07:20.700 --> 00:07:26.740
And then lastly, for the NPM1 mutated patients, and Gus and I were having this conversation this morning, what's the right third drug?

00:07:26.820 --> 00:07:27.820
Should it be a menin inhibitor?

00:07:27.900 --> 00:07:28.420
Should it be a FLT3?

00:07:28.440 --> 00:07:28.900
Should it be a FLT3 inhibitor?

00:07:28.980 --> 00:07:29.900
Should it be both drugs?

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:31.520
I don't think anybody really knows.

00:07:31.920 --> 00:07:35.880
And maybe quadruplets will be, like in myeloma, the new thing we shall see.

00:07:36.040 --> 00:07:36.680
Thanks for your attention.
